<DOC><DOCNO> AP900608-0197 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-90 2309EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-ArtRecovered     06-08 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Art Recovered,0186</SECOND><HEAD>Paintings Recovered Two Years After City's Largest Art Theft</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Some of the $6 million worth of paintings stolenin what police called the city's largest art theft have beenrecovered, the gallery director said Friday.   Nicholas Hall, director of Colnaghi USA Ltd. on Manhattan'swealthy Upper East Side, confirmed that some of the 19 Old Masterspaintings and eight drawings swiped have been found. A policedepartment spokesman, Officer Fred Weiner, couldn't immediatelyconfirm the recovery.   Hall said no one had been arrested yet in the theft. He would notsay which works were recovered and refused to provide furtherdetails, citing an ongoing police investigation.   The most valuable pieces stolen were two 15-by-7 inch wood panelsby the 15th century Italian Renaissance master, Fra Angelico. Thepanels, depicting saints, were worth a combined $4 million.   Works by Lodovico Carracci, Pacino Da Bonaguida, Paolo Catamara,Gasper Duguet and Jean-Baptiste-Simeon Chardin were also stolen.   In 1988, thieves broke in through a skylight in the brownstonewhere the gallery was located and shinnied down a rope.</TEXT></DOC>